I think a lot about the millennials, who were the last generation able to build connections with artists without the pressure of having a critical eye.
We arrived during the golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
One would dive directly into the matters without having to worry about the source, because it was not so easy to determine.
Without having any reason to question the pedestal on which they were placed, parasocial relationships had become the bases for our lives.
That's why we are so attached to nostalgia.
When The Office was still on air, my friends and I would order pizza and watch the series every Thursday.
It was nothing like what we have now with streaming, where all 12 episodes are available at once and where everyone watches at their own pace, starting social media posts with "spoiler alert" or continuing in specified private spaces.
inconsciously, one feels a strong desire to connect with the universal community that surrounded all of this.
That's why so many of us are obsessively watching shows like The Office or movies like "Head of State," which are full of short references, much like memes.
We repeated these references, knowing that most people knew them.
Now, even when something becomes completely viral, we can't know if everyone has seen it.
There's too much to see and no way to rationalize it all... will we escape hyper-saturation?
We get caught up in cycles of discovering new media, only to end up realizing that the artist is a predator or a fanatic.
We are forced to deal with a situation where we cling to nostalgia while recognizing that the people who created the art we connect with can be very imperfect.
We enter into parasocial relationships by paying more attention.
One understands that it is hard to reach these positions of wealth and power without crushing others along the way.
Due to a lack of collective consciousness regarding the media, we have developed a class consciousness that helps us remain critical.
Some of us continue to place people on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall off.
We're in a turbulent period, and I'm eager to find out where it will take us.
